Taylor Polynomials
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the cornerstones of numerical analysis is Taylor's theorem about
 which you learned in Calculus.
 A short study bears repeating here, however.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:Taylors"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Theorem ! Taylor's
\end_layout

\end_inset

For some integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

 derivatives on 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in(a,b)$
\end_inset

.
 Then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in(a,b)$
\end_inset

, there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

, depending on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, lying between 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=f(x_{0})+\sum_{j=1}^{n}\left(\frac{f^{(j)}(x_{0})}{j!}(x-x_{0})^{j}\right)+\frac{f^{(n+1)}(\xi)}{(n+1)!}(x-x_{0})^{n+1}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\noindent
In the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $x=x_{0}$
\end_inset

, the claim is trivial.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=x=x_{0}$
\end_inset

 will do.
 Now suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq x_{0}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be the open interval between 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{I}$
\end_inset

 be the closed interval between 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset\overline{I}\subset(a,b)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

 derivatives on 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)$
\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $f,f',f'',\ldots,f^{(n)}$
\end_inset

 are all continuous on 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{I}$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{(n+1)}$
\end_inset

 exists on 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 We now define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F(z)=f(x)-f(z)-\sum_{j=1}^{n}\frac{f^{(j)}(z)}{j!}(x-z)^{j}
\]

\end_inset

and will prove the theorem by showing that 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x_{0})=\frac{(x-x_{0})^{n+1}}{(n+1)!}f^{(n+1)}(\xi)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $F'(z)$
\end_inset

, a telescoping sum, is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
F'(z) & = & -f'(z)-\sum_{j=1}^{n}\left[\frac{f^{(j+1)}(z)}{j!}(x-z)^{j}-\frac{f^{(j)}(z)}{(j-1)!}(x-z)^{j-1}\right]\\
 & = & -f'(z)-\left[\frac{f^{(n+1)}(z)}{n!}(x-z)^{n}-f'(z)\right]\\
 & = & -\frac{f^{(n+1)}(z)}{n!}(x-z)^{n}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Now define 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z)=F(z)-\left(\frac{x-z}{x-x_{0}}\right)^{n+1}F(x_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to verify that 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 satisfies the premises of Rolle's theorem.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x_{0})=g(x)=0$
\end_inset

 and the continuity and differentiability criteria are met.
 By Rolle's theorem, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi\in I$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g'(\xi)=0=F'(\xi)+(n+1)\frac{(x-\xi)^{n}}{(x-x_{0})^{n-1}}F(x_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
F(x_{0}) & = & -F'(\xi)\frac{(x-x_{0})^{n+1}}{(n+1)(x-\xi)^{n}}\\
 & = & \frac{f^{(n+1)}(\xi)}{n!(n+1)}(x-x_{0})^{n+1}\\
 & = & \frac{f^{(n+1)}(\xi)}{(n+1)!}(x-x_{0})^{n+1}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

This completes the proof.
 
\end_layout

