\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

, are either unspecified or clear from context.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In calculus, you likely focused on the Taylor polynomial, or Taylor series,
 and did not pay much attention to the remainder term.
 The situation is quite the reverse in numerical analysis.
 Algorithmic error can often be ascertained by careful attention to the
 remainder term, making it more critical than the Taylor polynomial itself.
 The Taylor polynomial will, however, be used to derive certain methods,
 so won't be entirely neglected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most important thing to understand about the remainder term is that
 it tells us precisely how well 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{n}(x)$
\end_inset

 approximates 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 From Taylor's theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=T_{n}(x)+R_{n}(x)$
\end_inset

, so the absolute error in using 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{n}(x)$
\end_inset

 to approximate 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $|T_{n}(x)-f(x)|=|R_{n}(x)|$
\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $|R_{n}(x)|=\left|\frac{f^{(n+1)}(\xi)}{(n+1)!}(x-x_{0})^{n+1}\right|$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 between 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
|T_{n}(x)-f(x)|=|R_{n}(x)| & \leq & \max_{\xi}\left|\frac{f^{(n+1)}(\xi)}{(n+1)!}(x-x_{0})^{n+1}\right|\\
 & = & \frac{|x-x_{0}|^{n+1}}{(n+1)!}\max_{\xi}\left|f^{(n+1)}(\xi)\right|.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

We learn several things from this observation:
\end_layout

