 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $|R_{n}(x)|$
\end_inset

 measures exactly the absolute error 
\begin_inset Formula $|T_{n}(x)-f(x)|$
\end_inset

, we will be interested in conditions that force 
\begin_inset Formula $|R_{n}(x)|$
\end_inset

 to be small.
 According to observation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "enu:taylorObservation2"

\end_inset

, there are three quantities to consider.
 First, 
\begin_inset Formula $|x-x_{0}|^{n+1}$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $|x-x_{0}|$
\end_inset

, the distance between 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{n}(x)$
\end_inset

 will generally be better for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 closer to 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Second, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{(n+1)!}$
\end_inset

.
 This suggests that the more terms we use in our Taylor polynomial (the
 greater 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is), the better the approximation will be.
 Finally, 
\begin_inset Formula $|f^{(n+1)}(\xi)|$
\end_inset

, the magnitude of the 
\begin_inset Formula $(n+1)^{st}$
\end_inset

 derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 The tamer this derivative, the better 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{n}(x)$
\end_inset

 will approximate 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Be warned, however, these are just rules of thumb for making 
\begin_inset Formula $|R_{n}(x)|$
\end_inset

 small.
 There are exceptions to these rules.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To see these factors in action, consider 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=\ln(x)$
\end_inset

 expanded about 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}=e^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 According to Taylor's theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
T_{2}(x)=2+\frac{x-e^{2}}{e^{2}}-\frac{(x-e^{2})^{2}}{2e^{4}} & \mbox{ and } & R_{2}(x)=\frac{1}{3\xi^{3}}(x-e^{2})^{3};\\
T_{11}(x)=2+\sum_{j=1}^{11}\left(\frac{(-1)^{j-1}(x-e^{2})^{j}}{je^{2j}}\right) & \mbox{ and } & R_{11}(x)=\frac{-1}{12\xi^{12}}(x-e^{2})^{12}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

After you have convinced yourself these formulas are correct, suppose that
 we are interested in approximating 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln(x)$
\end_inset

 with an absolute error of no more than 
\begin_inset Formula $0.1$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $|\xi^{-3}|$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\xi^{-12}|$
\end_inset

 are decreasing functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

, they attain their maximum values on a closed interval at the lower endpoint
 of that interval.
 Hence, for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\geq e^{2}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $|R_{2}(x)|\leq\max_{\xi\in[e^{2},x]}\left|\frac{1}{3\xi^{3}}(x-e^{2})^{3}\right|=\frac{1}{3e^{6}}(x-e^{2})^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 But for 
\begin_inset Formula $0<x<e^{2}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $|R_{2}(x)|\leq\max_{\xi\in[x,e^{2}]}\left|\frac{1}{3\xi^{3}}(x-e^{2})^{3}\right|=\frac{1}{3x^{3}}(e^{2}-x)^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 To determine where these remainders are less than 
\begin_inset Formula $0.1$
\end_inset

, we need to solve the equations 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{3e^{6}}(x-e^{2})^{3}=0.1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{3x^{3}}(e^{2}-x)^{3}=0.1$
\end_inset

.
 The values we seek are 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\left(1+\sqrt[3]{\frac{3}{10}}\right)e^{2}\approx12.33$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\frac{\sqrt[3]{8100}+10\sqrt[3]{90}-30}{13\sqrt[3]{90}}e^{2}\approx4.427$
\end_inset

.
 So Taylor's theorem guarantees that 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}(x)$
\end_inset

 will approximate 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln(x)$
\end_inset

 to within 
\begin_inset Formula $0.1$
\end_inset

 over the entire interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[4.427,12.33]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{2}\approx7.389$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}(x)$
\end_inset

 approximates 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln(x)$
\end_inset

 to within 
\begin_inset Formula $0.1$
\end_inset

 from about 3 below 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{2}$
\end_inset

 to about 5 above 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is close enough to 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}=e^{2}$
\end_inset

, the approximation is good.
 A similar calculation for 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{11}(x)$
\end_inset

 reveals that 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{11}(x)$
\end_inset

 is guaranteed to approximate 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln(x)$
\end_inset

 to within 
\begin_inset Formula $0.1$
\end_inset

 over the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[3.667,14.89]$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, for a larger value of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 doesn't need to be as close to 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 to achieve the same accuracy.
\end_layout

