\begin_layout Standard
We now turn our attention to perhaps the most often analyzed Taylor polynomials-
–those for the sine and cosine functions.
 They provide examples with beautiful visualization and simple analysis.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{th}$
\end_inset

 Taylor polynomial for 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=\cos(x)$
\end_inset

 expanded about 0 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
T_{n}(x) & = & \cos(0)+\sum_{j=1}^{n}\left(\frac{\left.\frac{d^{j}}{dx^{j}}(\cos(x))\right|_{x=0}}{j!}(x-0)^{j}\right)\\
 & = & \cos(0)-\sin(0)\cdot x-\frac{\cos(0)}{2}x^{2}+\frac{\sin(0)}{6}x^{3}+\frac{\cos(0)}{24}x^{4}-\cdots\\
 & = & 1-\frac{1}{2}x^{2}+\frac{1}{24}x^{4}-\cdots
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and its remainder term is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
R_{n}(x) & = & \frac{\left.\frac{d^{n+1}}{dx^{n+1}}(\cos(x))\right|_{x=\xi}}{(n+1)!}(x-0)^{n+1}\\
 & = & \frac{x^{n+1}}{(n+1)!}\begin{cases}
-\sin(\xi) & \mbox{ when }n\mbox{ mod }4\equiv0\\
-\cos(\xi) & \mbox{ when }n\mbox{ mod }4\equiv1\\
\sin(\xi) & \mbox{ when }n\mbox{ mod }4\equiv2\\
\cos(\xi) & \mbox{ when }n\mbox{ mod }4\equiv3
\end{cases}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Since the sine and cosine functions are bounded between 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{|x|^{n+1}}{(n+1)!}\leq\frac{x^{n+1}}{(n+1)!}\sin\xi\leq\frac{|x|^{n+1}}{(n+1)!}$
\end_inset

 and similarly for 
\begin_inset Formula $-\sin\xi$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\xi$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $-\cos\xi$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, no matter which form the remainder term takes,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\frac{|x|^{n+1}}{(n+1)!}\leq R_{n}(x)\leq\frac{|x|^{n+1}}{(n+1)!}.
\]

\end_inset

There are two ways this remainder term will be small.
 First, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is close to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $|x|$
\end_inset

 is small, making 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{n}(x)$
