\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Unfortunately, the English translation of Taylor's theorem is only moderately
 helpful to anyone who is not well acquainted with early 
\begin_inset Formula $18^{th}$
\end_inset

 century mathematics.
 In 1715, function notation was still 20 years in the making.
 Today, we would interpret the declaration of the two variables as declaring
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 The claim in Theorem III is that we can rewrite 
\begin_inset Formula $x(z+v)$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $x+\underset{\dot{\ }}{x}\frac{v}{1\underset{\dot{\ }}{z}}+\underset{\ddot{\ }}{x}\frac{v\overset{\backslash}{v}}{1\cdot2\underset{\dot{\ }}{z}^{2}}+\underset{\dddot{\ }}{x}\frac{v\overset{\backslash}{v}\overset{\backslash\backslash}{v}}{1\cdot2\cdot3\underset{\dot{\ }}{z}^{3}}+\mbox{\&c}$
\end_inset

.
 Just as 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 should be interpreted as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 so should 
\begin_inset Formula $\underset{\dot{\ }}{x}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\underset{\ddot{\ }}{x}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\underset{\dddot{\ }}{x}$
\end_inset

.
 More precisely, 
\begin_inset Formula $\underset{\dot{\ }}{x}$
\end_inset

 means 
\begin_inset Formula $x(z+\underset{\dot{\ }}{z})-x(z)$
\end_inset

, the amount 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is incremented as 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is incremented by 
\begin_inset Formula $\underset{\dot{\ }}{z}$
\end_inset

.
 Likewise, 
\begin_inset Formula $\underset{\ddot{\ }}{x}$
\end_inset

 is the amount 
\begin_inset Formula $\underset{\dot{\ }}{x}$
\end_inset

 is incremented as 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is incremented by 
\begin_inset Formula $\underset{\dot{\ }}{z}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\underset{\ddot{\ }}{x}=\underset{\dot{\ }}{x}(z+\underset{\dot{\ }}{z})-\underset{\dot{\ }}{x}(z)=\left[x(z+2\underset{\dot{\ }}{z})-x(z+\underset{\dot{\ }}{z})\right]-\left[x(z+\underset{\dot{\ }}{z})-x(z)\right]=x(z+2\underset{\dot{\ }}{z})-2x(z+\underset{\dot{\ }}{z})+x(z)$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\underset{\dddot{\ }}{x}$
\end_inset

 is the amount 
\begin_inset Formula $\underset{\ddot{\ }}{x}$
\end_inset

 is incremented as 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is incremented by 
\begin_inset Formula $\underset{\dot{\ }}{z}$
\end_inset

.
 Now would be a good time to break from reading to verify that 
\begin_inset Formula $\underset{\dddot{\ }}{x}=x(z+3\underset{\dot{\ }}{z})-3x(z+2\underset{\dot{\ }}{z})+3x(z+\underset{\dot{\ }}{z})-x(z)$
\end_inset

, that 
\begin_inset Formula $\underset{\ddddot{\ }}{x}=x(z+4\underset{\dot{\ }}{z})-4x(z+3\underset{\dot{\ }}{z})+6x(z+2\underset{\dot{\ }}{z})-4x(z+\underset{\dot{\ }}{z})+x(z)$
\end_inset

, and so on.
 With this understanding and the conventions 
\begin_inset Formula $\underset{0}{x}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\underset{1}{x}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\underset{\dot{\ }}{x}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\underset{2}{x}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\underset{\ddot{\ }}{x}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overset{0}{v}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overset{1}{v}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\overset{^{\backslash}}{v}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overset{2}{v}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\overset{^{\backslash\backslash}}{v}$
\end_inset

, and so on, it is then an algebraic exercise to see that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
x(z+n\underset{\dot{\ }}{z}) & = & \sum_{j=0}^{n}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
j
\end{array}\right)\underset{^{j}}{x}=\underset{^{0}}{x}+\underset{^{1}}{x}\frac{n}{1}+\underset{^{2}}{x}\frac{n(n-1)}{1\cdot2}+\underset{^{3}}{x}\frac{n(n-1)(n-2)}{1\cdot2\cdot3}+\cdots+\underset{^{n}}{x}\frac{n(n-1)\cdots1}{1\cdot2\cdot3\cdots n}\\
 & = & \underset{^{0}}{x}+\underset{^{1}}{x}\frac{n\underset{\dot{\ }}{z}}{1\underset{\dot{\ }}{z}}+\underset{^{2}}{x}\frac{n\underset{\dot{\ }}{z}(n-1)\underset{\dot{\ }}{z}}{1\cdot2\underset{\dot{\ }}{z}^{2}}+\underset{^{3}}{x}\frac{n\underset{\dot{\ }}{z}(n-1)\underset{\dot{\ }}{z}(n-2)\underset{\dot{\ }}{z}}{1\cdot2\cdot3\underset{\dot{\ }}{z}^{3}}+\cdots+\underset{^{n}}{x}\frac{n\underset{\dot{\ }}{z}(n-1)\underset{\dot{\ }}{z}\cdots1\underset{\dot{\ }}{z}}{1\cdot2\cdot3\cdots n\underset{\dot{\ }}{z}^{n}}\\
 & = & \underset{^{0}}{x}+\underset{^{1}}{x}\frac{v}{1\underset{\dot{\ }}{z}}+\underset{^{2}}{x}\frac{v\overset{1}{v}}{1\cdot2\underset{\dot{\ }}{z}^{2}}+\underset{^{3}}{x}\frac{v\overset{2}{v}\overset{3}{v}}{1\cdot2\cdot3\underset{\dot{\ }}{z}^{3}}+\cdots+\underset{^{n}}{x}\frac{v\overset{2}{v}\overset{3}{v}\cdots\overset{n}{v}}{1\cdot2\cdot3\cdots n\underset{\dot{\ }}{z}^{n}}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

This calculation is essentially Taylor's proof of Theorem III.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Corollary II (which we would consider the theorem) is not proved by Taylor
 beyond the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

obvious
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 application of Newton's theory of fluxions.
 In today's language, corollary II follows by applying the limit as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

 to the expression from Theorem III.
 It makes for another nice exercise to verify that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{\underset{k}{x}}{\underset{\dot{\ }}{z}^{k}}=x^{(k)}(z)$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{th}$
\end_inset

 derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 And one final exercise to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\to\infty}\overset{k}{v}=v$
\end_inset

.
